WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.497 --> 00:00:08.580
(gentle piano music)

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:11.460
- [Narrator] We are the paradoxical ape.

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:14.910
Bipedal, naked,

00:00:14.910 --> 00:00:15.923
large-brained,

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:20.630
long the master of fire,
tools, and language

00:00:21.630 --> 00:00:24.023
but still trying to understand ourselves.

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:27.903
Aware that death is inevitable,

00:00:29.190 --> 00:00:30.863
yet filled with optimism,

00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:36.243
we grow up slowly, we hand down knowledge,

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:39.283
we empathize and deceive.

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:42.020
We shape the future

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:44.693
from our shared understanding of the past.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:48.430
CARTA brings together experts

00:00:48.430 --> 00:00:51.373
from diverse disciplines
to exchange insights

00:00:51.373 --> 00:00:55.398
on who we are and how we got here,

00:00:55.398 --> 00:00:57.960
an exploration made possible

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:00.737
by the generosity of humans like you.

00:01:46.936 --> 00:01:48.130
- Thank you everyone for coming,

00:01:48.130 --> 00:01:50.660
and I'll just take a moment to tell you

00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:52.220
a little bit about how we decided

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:56.530
to make like a CARTA meeting
entirely on human imagination.

00:01:56.530 --> 00:01:58.140
This is one of those things that,

00:01:58.140 --> 00:02:01.010
it seems to happen only in San Diego

00:02:01.010 --> 00:02:03.296
where two people and I'm
talking about myself,

00:02:03.296 --> 00:02:06.360
who I'm a professor in pediatrics

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:08.810
and cellular molecular
medicine, turns out to be

00:02:08.810 --> 00:02:11.950
in a meeting sitting
together with Sheldon Brown,

00:02:11.950 --> 00:02:13.740
who you're going to
hear as a first speaker,

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:16.340
and Sheldon Brown comes from visual arts.

00:02:16.340 --> 00:02:19.280
So, a scientist and an
artist, we start talking

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:21.420
and we realized we have
something in common.

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:24.380
We are both fascinated
by human imagination.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:27.280
So I make a challenge to Sheldon,

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:30.420
and say well can we put this
in a scientific context,

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:34.320
and we start planning
about a meeting like that

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:36.590
and we realized that most of the time,

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:39.029
when we try to understand something,

00:02:39.029 --> 00:02:43.200
if it's unique or enhanced in humans,

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:48.200
we turn on to compare
our closest relative,

00:02:48.290 --> 00:02:50.480
living relative, such as the chimpanzee,

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:53.410
and comparing to other
animals is difficult,

00:02:53.410 --> 00:02:55.390
especially if you're
talking about cognition

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:57.540
and imagination, so this time,

00:02:57.540 --> 00:02:59.440
I think you're going to
hear lots of speakers

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:01.962
talking about imagination in modern humans

00:03:01.962 --> 00:03:06.024
and also in extinct humans
such as the Neanderthals,

00:03:06.024 --> 00:03:09.670
and we hope that the combination
of all those speakers,

00:03:09.670 --> 00:03:12.190
all this knowledge, will
help us to understand

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:14.040
a little bit about ourselves

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:17.510
and answer those questions
that Ajit posed to us.

00:03:17.510 --> 00:03:22.220
- Okay, so we're going to
move into a new space in time

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:24.720
right now, we're going
to move into the night.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:29.720
Some 3,500 years ago, humans
engineered control of fire.

00:03:29.950 --> 00:03:31.932
It's actually quite complicated.

00:03:31.932 --> 00:03:36.540
There was a huge caloric gain from food,

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:40.930
because cooked food makes
many more calories available.

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:44.450
Protection from predators,
but what's most interesting

00:03:44.450 --> 00:03:46.561
about it is that humans extended the day

00:03:46.561 --> 00:03:49.920
by four or five hours to become

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:52.533
the shortest sleepers of all primates.

00:03:55.986 --> 00:04:00.480
And, the time that gained was
economically unproductive.

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:03.380
No more calories were going
in, nothing was happening

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:06.560
economically, and yet the physical changes

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:11.560
in ciracdian rhythms were
enormous to extend the day,

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:16.950
and there were some very major impacts

00:04:16.950 --> 00:04:19.500
on health from reduction in melatonin

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:22.260
and other things, so there were costs.

00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:25.420
So the question is, why?

00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:28.220
You know why was this selected for,

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:29.889
why didn't we just go to sleep?

00:04:29.889 --> 00:04:33.770
So what I'm going to suggest
here is that firelight

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:36.091
opened up a new time and space

00:04:36.091 --> 00:04:40.040
for the imagination and for the arts.

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:42.867
There's the wonderful
quote from a German writer:

00:04:42.867 --> 00:04:44.479
"Nobody sees anything in the night;

00:04:44.479 --> 00:04:47.457
"everybody sees something in the night."

00:04:48.610 --> 00:04:52.230
So, this is, the night is often
the time of the imagination

00:04:52.230 --> 00:04:55.506
if I would define the
imagination for this talk

00:04:55.506 --> 00:04:57.889
as the ability to form mental images

00:04:57.889 --> 00:05:01.030
of something not present to the senses

00:05:01.030 --> 00:05:03.593
and never wholly perceived in reality.

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.544
So, what transpires by day and night,

00:05:07.544 --> 00:05:10.910
why do firelight hours matter?

00:05:10.910 --> 00:05:13.260
Well this is not so easy to find out,

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:14.850
but I became very interested in this

00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:19.800
among the Ju'hoansi bushmen
of Botswana and Namibia.

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:20.950
These are a group of people

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:22.870
who live by hunting and gathering.

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:26.150
They utilize about 100 plant species,

00:05:26.150 --> 00:05:29.330
30 animal species, and in the hard times,

00:05:29.330 --> 00:05:31.060
a few of them even have to gather water.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:34.223
The only water they get is
from melon or from roots.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:39.650
And they live in very small
camps of 25 to 40 people

00:05:39.650 --> 00:05:43.840
with egalitarian structure, age hierarchy

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:46.223
and recognized camp leaders.

00:05:47.244 --> 00:05:49.970
So the interaction, scale of interaction

00:05:49.970 --> 00:05:52.950
in every day life is very very small.

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:56.143
And yet they have these
incredibly sophisticated

00:05:56.143 --> 00:06:00.180
social institutions, and the question is,

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:02.030
when you live on a postage stamp,

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:03.923
you know, how do you see the big picture?

00:06:03.923 --> 00:06:06.480
So that was my question,
to see what happens

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:08.440
in the day and the night.

00:06:08.440 --> 00:06:10.148
Here are some of the cultural institutions

00:06:10.148 --> 00:06:14.418
that they have: complex kinship systems,

00:06:14.418 --> 00:06:19.418
defining both biological and
imaginary or fictive kin.

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:21.770
These systems are so complicated that I,

00:06:21.770 --> 00:06:23.200
after 30 years of working there,

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:25.219
am still trying to figure them out.

00:06:25.219 --> 00:06:26.280
(audience laughs)

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:28.615
Rules for widespread food sharing,

00:06:28.615 --> 00:06:32.776
they have arranged marriage
and elaborate marriage rites,

00:06:32.776 --> 00:06:35.426
sophisticated systems of land tenure,

00:06:35.426 --> 00:06:39.140
trance healing in an
unbelievable communication

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:42.699
with the spirit world, and
then networks of xaro exchange,

00:06:42.699 --> 00:06:46.300
widespread access to
the resources of others,

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:48.530
people move around, we'll see this.

00:06:48.530 --> 00:06:50.050
So what happens at day and night,

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:51.734
that was my question.

00:06:51.734 --> 00:06:56.734
And with data in 1974,
I collected information

00:06:57.850 --> 00:07:01.300
on day and night conversations with groups

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:05.234
of five or more adults
longer than 15 to 20 minutes,

00:07:05.234 --> 00:07:10.234
and then 2011 and 2013, I
collected the full stories

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:12.568
and had the transcribed and translated

00:07:12.568 --> 00:07:16.330
by a team of Ju'hoansi who
are now working with laptops

00:07:16.330 --> 00:07:19.492
and sending me the most amazing emails.

00:07:19.492 --> 00:07:20.670
(audience laughs)

00:07:20.670 --> 00:07:23.327
All the gossip comes through by email now.

00:07:23.327 --> 00:07:25.010
(audience laughs)

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:28.850
So, the day talk which
was really interesting,

00:07:28.850 --> 00:07:33.406
was the topics of conversation
are largely practical,

00:07:33.406 --> 00:07:35.870
economic issues and planning,

00:07:35.870 --> 00:07:38.603
an enormous amount of
complaint and criticism

00:07:38.603 --> 00:07:40.305
(audience laughs)

00:07:40.305 --> 00:07:42.410
as people get on to each
other's case, gossip,

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:45.480
and people say, "Well gossip
maintains social norms,"

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.740
but in fact I found 30
to 40% of the gossip

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:51.210
was just total bull--
(audience laughs)

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:54.700
It was constructed for social strategies.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:57.467
And so you can see that, that was the day,

00:07:57.467 --> 00:08:00.870
and then there's the switch to the night.

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:02.630
All day long as an anthropologist,

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:04.767
people are on my case to give me things,

00:08:04.767 --> 00:08:07.410
to give them things, to help with things.

00:08:07.410 --> 00:08:09.080
At the night, that's off limits.

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:11.935
Everything mellows off and
I don't get a single demand.

00:08:11.935 --> 00:08:15.587
Isak Dinesen, or Karen Blixen, wrote,

00:08:15.587 --> 00:08:17.957
"At times I believe that
my feet have been set

00:08:17.957 --> 00:08:20.917
"upon a road which I
shall go on following,

00:08:20.917 --> 00:08:24.057
"and that slowly the center
of gravity of my being

00:08:24.057 --> 00:08:26.372
"will shift over from
the world of the day,

00:08:26.372 --> 00:08:29.287
"from the domain of
organizing and regulating

00:08:29.287 --> 00:08:32.573
"universal powers, into the
world of the imagination,

00:08:32.573 --> 00:08:34.597
"with the coming of the dusk,

00:08:34.597 --> 00:08:39.060
"with the lighting of the first
star and the first candle."

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:41.490
And that's the transition you feel,

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:45.221
so I looked at nights, at
36 nights, in four camps.

00:08:45.221 --> 00:08:48.110
Eight nights were singing, music,

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:49.980
singing, gathering together.

00:08:49.980 --> 00:08:52.250
Six nights were trance healing dances,

00:08:52.250 --> 00:08:55.910
and most nights were
conversation and storytelling,

00:08:55.910 --> 00:09:00.200
and that's where I
recorded the conversations.

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:04.180
And the results were quite astounding.

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:06.804
All you really need to do
is look at the orange here.

00:09:06.804 --> 00:09:10.040
Oh actually the print is pretty big,

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:12.740
but you can see, in the
day there are few stories.

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:14.168
Economic complaint.

00:09:14.168 --> 00:09:16.829
At night, people get
off each other's cases

00:09:16.829 --> 00:09:20.055
and they mostly sit
around and tell stories,

00:09:20.055 --> 00:09:25.055
and come together, and so the moods mellow

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:26.990
when the suns set, and I can tell you,

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:29.924
it's very harsh in the day,
because it's a sharing economy

00:09:29.924 --> 00:09:32.326
and people are always mad

00:09:32.326 --> 00:09:34.410
that he gave that to her and not to me.

00:09:34.410 --> 00:09:36.480
And people gather around single fires

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:38.326
to talk and to story.

00:09:38.326 --> 00:09:40.185
They talk about their own experiences

00:09:40.185 --> 00:09:43.984
or those of others in a very entrancic,

00:09:43.984 --> 00:09:46.734
entrancing, compelling rhythmic language.

00:09:46.734 --> 00:09:50.620
The listeners are stunned with suspense,

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:53.061
rolling with laughter, close to tears,

00:09:53.061 --> 00:09:56.410
and emotions are synchronized,

00:09:56.410 --> 00:09:59.753
because everybody is
relating to the same story.

00:09:59.753 --> 00:10:03.210
The people they talk
about are often people

00:10:03.210 --> 00:10:04.910
who are 200 kilometers away,

00:10:04.910 --> 00:10:07.760
and they bring that person
right to the hearth,

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:10.654
so delicious are the details of the story.

00:10:10.654 --> 00:10:15.442
But the storytelling, what
I'm going to suggest here,

00:10:15.442 --> 00:10:18.537
is that it gives the
big picture of society.

00:10:18.537 --> 00:10:22.385
Good storytellers transmit
visions of social institutions

00:10:22.385 --> 00:10:26.020
that are imaginary, like kinship system,

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:30.380
exchange systems, and they're
not present to the senses.

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:32.778
They're never wholly perceived in reality,

00:10:32.778 --> 00:10:36.250
but the people, the few
people, like this old lady,

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:40.060
who can put stories together
to imagine the big picture

00:10:40.060 --> 00:10:44.780
of society and tell about it,
they become very influential,

00:10:44.780 --> 00:10:46.160
these are the organizers

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:48.663
and the mediators who have this skill.

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:51.860
This is an example of xaro exchange.

00:10:51.860 --> 00:10:55.810
This is an exchange of gifts
where people choose partners,

00:10:55.810 --> 00:10:59.280
up to 200 kilometers away,
that longest line there

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:03.316
is 200 kilometers, and this
is a social security system

00:11:03.316 --> 00:11:06.260
so they keep exchanging gifts

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:08.161
and the underlying relationship is,

00:11:08.161 --> 00:11:09.930
when you're in trouble, I'll help you,

00:11:09.930 --> 00:11:12.740
you can come live with me,
and when I'm in trouble,

00:11:12.740 --> 00:11:16.840
you can come live with me,
so that is the exchange.

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:20.351
The average person has about
15 or 16 of these partners,

00:11:20.351 --> 00:11:24.713
and they usually spend about
two to three months a year

00:11:24.713 --> 00:11:26.650
living with these partners.

00:11:26.650 --> 00:11:29.114
This old lady is wearing all her gifts

00:11:29.114 --> 00:11:33.080
to advertise herself because
she's trying to marry off

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:36.348
her grandson, and she's
showing how welcome she is.

00:11:36.348 --> 00:11:41.348
And then, we have the
stories give the big picture

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:44.620
of regional gatherings, xaro exchange

00:11:44.620 --> 00:11:48.780
and kin relations, and
the one story I collected,

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:52.880
it was from the 1940s,
six bands coming together

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:57.234
at a particularly good time of
year to harvest moramo beans

00:11:57.234 --> 00:12:00.950
and this story goes on for pages,

00:12:00.950 --> 00:12:03.190
and the relations between
the bands are described,

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:08.190
and the complex kinship
relations are described,

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:11.060
everybody named would
tell how they are related

00:12:11.060 --> 00:12:15.090
to so-and-so and so-and-so, and so-and-so.

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:17.012
This gives you an idea of the area

00:12:17.012 --> 00:12:19.298
from which people came for this gathering.

00:12:19.298 --> 00:12:22.603
The whole thing would be about
oh, two or 300 kilometers,

00:12:22.603 --> 00:12:27.603
north south, and this is sort
of an excerpt from the story.

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:32.020
Different people were
there, some were there

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:34.520
from the N/olau Eiseb Valley,

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:37.020
and some were Nharo
from the further south.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:38.610
Some from the N/on/oni si

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:42.250
where there is a forest with
lots of combretum trees.

00:12:42.250 --> 00:12:43.704
The norther people were there also,

00:12:43.704 --> 00:12:46.640
they were called /Uisi also came.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:50.110
The owners of N(clicking
twice)ola'a also came, so,

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:54.550
and then they tell how everyone
is related, this story.

00:12:54.550 --> 00:12:56.060
And this is a story put together

00:12:56.060 --> 00:12:58.730
from many that she had heard
because she was a little girl

00:12:58.730 --> 00:13:01.190
when this had happened,
and then they described

00:13:01.190 --> 00:13:02.430
what happened at the gathering.

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:04.150
This goes on for pages.

00:13:04.150 --> 00:13:05.660
She got the other skin apron

00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:08.330
and gave it to my late
grandmother N/hakxa n/a.

00:13:08.330 --> 00:13:09.777
She took out another skin apron

00:13:09.777 --> 00:13:12.400
and gave it to her aunt,
the late N=aisa n/a'an.

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:14.170
And then she gave out more gifts,

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:16.340
and then it was the
beginning of gift giving.

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:19.387
He, /Kagece, tried to
pull the beaded headband

00:13:19.387 --> 00:13:21.480
on his head but it didn't fit,

00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:23.343
so he took it off his head
and gave it to my granny

00:13:23.343 --> 00:13:26.550
N/hakxa n/a and gave other things to her,

00:13:26.550 --> 00:13:28.908
and this goes on and on and on, so.

00:13:28.908 --> 00:13:33.250
And you don't only have stories

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:34.680
but for the other form of arts,

00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:37.409
you have gifts, so that these partnerships

00:13:37.409 --> 00:13:41.500
of mutual obligation are
marked by gift exchange,

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:45.300
beautifully made, artistically made gifts,

00:13:45.300 --> 00:13:48.325
and these gifts represent relationships

00:13:48.325 --> 00:13:52.010
but they also carry stories
of who gave them to whom.

00:13:52.010 --> 00:13:53.960
They go through long chains of giving,

00:13:53.960 --> 00:13:57.322
so you know, they create
these huge networks

00:13:57.322 --> 00:14:01.790
so each gift would have
a history in stories.

00:14:01.790 --> 00:14:04.750
And then another example
would be in marriage,

00:14:04.750 --> 00:14:07.740
you don't see many marriage
when you live in a small band

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:10.499
of 25 people, you may see
a few in your lifetime,

00:14:10.499 --> 00:14:14.480
and they're infrequent but the procedures

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:16.480
are elaborate, they're arranged.

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:21.480
Usually the girl is married
around 13 and rejects the man,

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:26.450
and makes a big fuss and
these stories are hilarious,

00:14:26.450 --> 00:14:28.877
of old ladies telling about
how they rejected their husband

00:14:28.877 --> 00:14:31.670
and ran away and destroyed
the wedding gifts

00:14:31.670 --> 00:14:34.900
and this prepares young
people for marriage,

00:14:34.900 --> 00:14:37.606
knowing that the first years
are going to be kind of rough,

00:14:37.606 --> 00:14:40.641
(audience laughs)

00:14:40.641 --> 00:14:42.407
and that they'll get used to them,

00:14:42.407 --> 00:14:46.164
and then parents also learn
of all the case studies

00:14:46.164 --> 00:14:49.170
of marriage told in stories

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:50.940
and they know how to manage them.

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:55.470
Okay, the other thing which
is people, N/uasi people do,

00:14:55.470 --> 00:14:58.870
trance healing in which the
women sit and clap all night

00:14:58.870 --> 00:15:02.100
and sing, and the men, the trance healers,

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:05.066
travel to the spirit
world where they negotiate

00:15:05.066 --> 00:15:10.066
with the spirits, asking
them not to take people away,

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:13.860
to leave them on Earth,
that they love them,

00:15:13.860 --> 00:15:15.950
giving everyone preventative medicine.

00:15:15.950 --> 00:15:20.042
In these stories, the
trance healers at night

00:15:20.042 --> 00:15:22.790
will tell about how far they traveled,

00:15:22.790 --> 00:15:24.948
I mean, I was once
telling people how about,

00:15:24.948 --> 00:15:26.740
we're sending men to the moon

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:28.607
and there's an old guy
who looked at me and said,

00:15:28.607 --> 00:15:31.800
"Been there."
(audience laughs)

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:36.800
So, this is you know, you can imagine, so,

00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:39.910
the trancers then, in telling the stories,

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:42.484
connect people with a shared cosmology,

00:15:42.484 --> 00:15:45.540
a shared sense of the spirit world,

00:15:45.540 --> 00:15:48.653
a shared sense of what causes misfortune.

00:15:49.570 --> 00:15:53.160
So, sort of to wrap up then,
day, night and the imagination,

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:58.160
so the day, you have
economics, technology,

00:15:58.480 --> 00:16:00.739
nitty-gritty of social relations.

00:16:00.739 --> 00:16:05.722
The night, the stories
are about imagined roles,

00:16:05.722 --> 00:16:10.065
rules, communities, that are not tangible

00:16:10.065 --> 00:16:13.670
or physically coherent in time and space.

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:17.730
So they're imagining society
in their social institutions.

00:16:17.730 --> 00:16:20.486
They also imagine as change comes,

00:16:20.486 --> 00:16:22.890
they can also imagine, they can innovate,

00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:24.777
and imagine changes as well.

00:16:24.777 --> 00:16:28.708
And then stories stimulate imaginations

00:16:28.708 --> 00:16:32.030
to construct the big picture
of social institutions

00:16:32.030 --> 00:16:36.590
and relations, and very very importantly,

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:38.230
because we have theory of mind,

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:40.528
because we can read what
other people are thinking,

00:16:40.528 --> 00:16:42.988
they really make people imagine

00:16:42.988 --> 00:16:45.420
the thoughts and the feelings of others,

00:16:45.420 --> 00:16:47.640
so that you can really understand

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:50.040
that people feel differently about things,

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:53.370
and it brings a lot of
understanding into it,

00:16:53.370 --> 00:16:54.890
and people put themselves

00:16:54.890 --> 00:16:57.090
in other people's shoes in the stories,

00:16:57.090 --> 00:17:01.230
because they're so emotionally
laded, it's incredible.

00:17:01.230 --> 00:17:03.870
So essentially what I found in this study

00:17:03.870 --> 00:17:07.334
is that the evening hours provide a space

00:17:07.334 --> 00:17:10.590
for the arts and for the imagination.

00:17:10.590 --> 00:17:15.590
And the arts would include
also music, dance and stories,

00:17:15.622 --> 00:17:19.440
and does this happen beyond the Kalahari?

00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:21.253
We've moved up to the Arctic now.

00:17:22.610 --> 00:17:26.180
Yes, these kinds of stories are told

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:28.604
in all hunter-gatherer societies at night.

00:17:28.604 --> 00:17:31.320
If you look through the
human relation area files,

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:36.320
there are 38 mentions
of sanctioning gossip,

00:17:36.847 --> 00:17:39.510
