00:22:23.090 --> 00:22:24.530
How do you make reconstructions?

00:22:24.530 --> 00:22:27.792
First, you need a skull.

00:22:27.792 --> 00:22:32.391
We often get casts of skulls,
or we've made casts ourselves,

00:22:32.391 --> 00:22:35.650
or, if you want to
reconstruct a total body,

00:22:35.650 --> 00:22:39.890
we get bags of all elements of pieces,

00:22:39.890 --> 00:22:44.890
mostly pieces of human skeletons,

00:22:45.320 --> 00:22:48.330
and these pieces we try to put together,

00:22:48.330 --> 00:22:51.123
to reconstruct a complete skeleton,

00:22:51.123 --> 00:22:54.035
and for example here, we got a skull,

00:22:54.035 --> 00:22:57.340
and it's missing its face, and we got only

00:22:58.382 --> 00:23:00.570
a couple of bits of the face.

00:23:00.570 --> 00:23:04.920
So we look in our big spare
part collection behind me.

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:07.590
We have an enormous
collection here of skulls.

00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:09.480
In the drawers are also post cranial stuff

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:14.450
and in it here, you can
get all kind of bones

00:23:15.620 --> 00:23:19.803
and pelvis pieces.
- It's our garage.

00:23:19.803 --> 00:23:22.143
- Our garage, we're going
to look in our collection,

00:23:22.143 --> 00:23:25.690
what type of human is this?

00:23:25.690 --> 00:23:28.330
How old is it, you have to know of course,

00:23:28.330 --> 00:23:30.700
and what type is it, and then
we look in our collection.

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:34.590
If we find other individuals
for the same timeframe,

00:23:34.590 --> 00:23:38.047
and then we're going to
look at what our bits are,

00:23:38.047 --> 00:23:40.860
are they the same type of morphology,

00:23:40.860 --> 00:23:44.583
and then we try to recreate more or less

00:23:44.583 --> 00:23:48.070
the face on the skull.

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:50.460
- This is end result of the
reconstruction of this face,

00:23:50.460 --> 00:23:55.020
so we use this one as
base, we have this part

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:58.890
and all those loose parts,
and then we create new face.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:02.089
If you see carefully, you see
the maxilla that was used,

00:24:02.089 --> 00:24:06.432
the left maxilla of this face
is put here in this part,

00:24:06.432 --> 00:24:09.440
and the nasal area, we
used also this piece

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:14.440
from Atapuerca, we use here,
so we can recreate a new face.

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:17.740
- But nowadays, lot of
skull reconstructions

00:24:17.740 --> 00:24:20.867
are more made with scintigraphy.

00:24:21.820 --> 00:24:26.170
They made, they scan the
bones so it's not necessary

00:24:26.170 --> 00:24:30.491
to do this, to make
casts of the originals,

00:24:30.491 --> 00:24:33.853
so we scan, the bones
are scanned nowadays,

00:24:35.188 --> 00:24:38.503
and at home we've got a 3D printer

00:24:39.930 --> 00:24:43.078
and you can print out the bones without,

00:24:43.078 --> 00:24:47.150
I have to use silicones of originals.

00:24:47.150 --> 00:24:51.450
It's even today possible
to make a reconstruction

00:24:51.450 --> 00:24:54.390
from the skull while still in situ,

00:24:54.390 --> 00:24:57.080
embedded in calcite in the cave.

00:24:57.080 --> 00:24:59.565
This one is from Altamura and we got,

00:24:59.565 --> 00:25:03.290
they managed to scan the skull in the cave

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:07.350
embedded in calcite, and then
we printed out the skull,

00:25:07.350 --> 00:25:10.490
and then we were able to
make a reconstruction.

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:11.500
- This is the result of the skull,

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:13.820
and you see these small
pegs here in the face,

00:25:13.820 --> 00:25:16.870
and those pegs resemble the skin thickness

00:25:16.870 --> 00:25:18.470
in this part of the face.

00:25:18.470 --> 00:25:19.770
So if you see here on the cheeks,

00:25:19.770 --> 00:25:22.210
you see bigger pegs, longer pegs,

00:25:22.210 --> 00:25:25.170
those are lot of more fat
tissue and bigger muscles,

00:25:25.170 --> 00:25:27.300
especially here off the areas,

00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:32.160
and this side, you see the
big muscle for chewing,

00:25:32.160 --> 00:25:33.670
and big temple muscle here

00:25:33.670 --> 00:25:36.630
and you see this peg is rather long

00:25:36.630 --> 00:25:38.380
because the muscle is very thick.

00:25:38.380 --> 00:25:40.801
On the nose, the skin is very thin,

00:25:40.801 --> 00:25:43.060
and there are no muscles,
not so much muscles on it,

00:25:43.060 --> 00:25:44.700
small ones, so you see the pegs,

00:25:44.700 --> 00:25:49.530
the tissue thickness is very
small, is very not so big.

00:25:49.530 --> 00:25:52.007
- To guide us with the
reconstruction and especially

00:25:52.007 --> 00:25:55.160
to choose the right muscle size

00:25:55.160 --> 00:26:00.160
and how the muscles are,
we look at dead corpses.

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:04.060
We dissect dead corpses of chimps,

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:07.660
and also we can look at the institutes

00:26:07.660 --> 00:26:10.789
where they have dead bodies of people,

00:26:10.789 --> 00:26:14.479
so we can...
- Recreate.

00:26:14.479 --> 00:26:19.479
- Recreate the muscles
from the modern humans.

00:26:19.860 --> 00:26:23.330
So these muscles guide us
with the reconstruction

00:26:23.330 --> 00:26:26.720
of these in between human ancestors

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:29.414
who are a little bit
apelike in the face also,

00:26:29.414 --> 00:26:32.957
especially the oldest
ones, but become more

00:26:32.957 --> 00:26:36.394
and more and more humanlike,

00:26:36.394 --> 00:26:40.157
so we have to look more
at the human muscles.

