00:37:23.220 --> 00:37:25.827
- I will, I'll show the work that we do,

00:37:25.827 --> 00:37:28.700
and in a way it's quite
similar to the Kennis brothers.

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:31.230
We try to reconstruct
parts of the Neanderthal,

00:37:31.230 --> 00:37:32.989
but instead of body parts,

00:37:32.989 --> 00:37:36.324
what we try to do is
reconstruct their minds.

00:37:36.324 --> 00:37:39.070
One day I imagined that would be possible,

00:37:39.070 --> 00:37:40.960
and I don't have a
brother to challenge me,

00:37:40.960 --> 00:37:43.110
to keep it going, but I have a whole team,

00:37:43.110 --> 00:37:45.787
and this whole team
helped me to achieve that,

00:37:45.787 --> 00:37:47.791
and that's what I'm going
to share with you guys.

00:37:47.791 --> 00:37:52.480
So we start with the idea
that perhaps we should study

00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:54.950
human imaginations by
comparing to other humans,

00:37:54.950 --> 00:37:58.259
perhaps, humans that have a
different kind of imagination,

00:37:58.259 --> 00:38:02.000
either worse or better, just different.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:03.890
And we thought about Neanderthals,
and part of the reason

00:38:03.890 --> 00:38:07.400
is because we know more
about the Neanderthals

00:38:07.400 --> 00:38:11.140
than the other extinct hominids,

00:38:11.140 --> 00:38:15.792
and we also shared our world
with them for a long time.

00:38:15.792 --> 00:38:19.420
It becomes clear, and I think
you guys all learn about that,

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:22.495
that during the time
period of the Neanderthals,

00:38:22.495 --> 00:38:27.495
on Earth, I mean, they
developed these stone tools

00:38:28.540 --> 00:38:31.056
and definitely make it better,

00:38:31.056 --> 00:38:33.309
but the technology
didn't go as far as that,

00:38:33.309 --> 00:38:36.490
and in contrast, we modern humans,

00:38:36.490 --> 00:38:38.200
in a very short period of time,

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:40.624
we could create not only stone tools,

00:38:40.624 --> 00:38:43.700
but a whole set of new technology, arts,

00:38:43.700 --> 00:38:46.945
and sophisticated ways to
communicate with each other,

00:38:46.945 --> 00:38:50.000
so which points out
that perhaps our brains

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.711
are somehow different from them.

00:38:52.711 --> 00:38:54.928
So, how do we study the Neanderthals

00:38:54.928 --> 00:38:57.399
and how we can start
tracking these questions?

00:38:57.399 --> 00:39:00.143
So we have bones, we have endocasts

00:39:00.143 --> 00:39:03.290
that we can predict how their brains

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:06.700
would have different shape or volume.

00:39:06.700 --> 00:39:08.200
We have DNA.

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:09.935
We can extract DNA from
bones of Neanderthals,

00:39:09.935 --> 00:39:13.830
and we have impressions and
someone might call that art,

00:39:13.830 --> 00:39:15.570
others might not think that this is art,

00:39:15.570 --> 00:39:17.760
but they definitely left some impressions

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:19.507
for us to try to understand.

00:39:19.507 --> 00:39:23.060
So from the endocasts, this
is the work from the group

00:39:23.060 --> 00:39:27.880
from Leipzig, in Germany,
they have confirmed

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:30.770
that their brains, at
least in terms of volume,

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:32.700
is not so different than us.

00:39:32.700 --> 00:39:35.100
They actually have a
little bit larger brain

00:39:35.100 --> 00:39:36.621
compared to what we have.

00:39:36.621 --> 00:39:39.664
But, I mean the endocast
doesn't offer too much

00:39:39.664 --> 00:39:42.619
in terms of how that
brain actually functioned.

00:39:42.619 --> 00:39:47.619
So, Svante Paabo, also
from Leipzig, is a pioneer

00:39:48.700 --> 00:39:51.964
on isolating the DNA from the Neanderthals

00:39:51.964 --> 00:39:54.950
and sequenced them so
we can actually compare

00:39:54.950 --> 00:39:57.563
the Neanderthal genome
to the modern human's.

00:39:58.820 --> 00:40:00.770
So this is all nice, but actually,

00:40:00.770 --> 00:40:04.310
how do we understand the Neanderthal brain

00:40:04.310 --> 00:40:06.580
or the Neanderthal mind in a dish?

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:08.580
So I come from a stem cell background

00:40:08.580 --> 00:40:10.250
and in stem cells, we have something

00:40:10.250 --> 00:40:14.190
that's called brain organoid,
also called a mini-brain,

00:40:14.190 --> 00:40:15.740
because we can recreate those

00:40:15.740 --> 00:40:18.492
using human pluripotent stem cells.

00:40:18.492 --> 00:40:20.980
They don't look like that.
(audience laughs)

00:40:20.980 --> 00:40:23.864
They're actually a simplified,
miniaturized version

00:40:23.864 --> 00:40:27.420
of the human brain, and we have a recipe

00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:30.095
that we developed in the
lab, that is quite good

00:40:30.095 --> 00:40:34.500
to make a functional mini
brain, or brain organoids,

00:40:34.500 --> 00:40:36.680
and it always starts from single cells.

00:40:36.680 --> 00:40:39.640
These are similar to embryonic stem cells,

00:40:39.640 --> 00:40:41.340
or pluripotent stem cells

00:40:41.340 --> 00:40:43.110
that we can reprogram from people.

00:40:43.110 --> 00:40:46.960
I can do it from my cells,
from your cells as well.

00:40:46.960 --> 00:40:50.659
So from these single cells, we
grow them in different media,

00:40:50.659 --> 00:40:52.232
changing the growth factors,

00:40:52.232 --> 00:40:55.080
specific growth factors
at different stages,

00:40:55.080 --> 00:40:58.790
until we can mature
them and these networks

00:40:58.790 --> 00:41:01.490
will just form and become
more and more sophisticated.

00:41:01.490 --> 00:41:05.270
Another thing is that,
I mean they can grow

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:08.010
up to a half centimeter
and we can keep them alive

00:41:08.010 --> 00:41:11.630
for up to two years, so these
are quite robust protocols,

00:41:11.630 --> 00:41:13.690
because not only you create a single one,

00:41:13.690 --> 00:41:16.500
but it can create thousands
of brain organoids

00:41:16.500 --> 00:41:19.110
in the same batch, so that allows you

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:21.302
to do some experiments with them.

00:41:21.302 --> 00:41:25.500
If you cut one of those spheres,

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:28.620
what you can see is that they maintain,

00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:31.660
or they mimic, some of the
embryonic brain structures

00:41:31.660 --> 00:41:35.110
in humans, by having a
ventricular zone in the center,

00:41:35.110 --> 00:41:37.140
that's stem cells that migrate out

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:39.630
and form what we call the cortical plate.

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:42.320
As these organoids age,
these cortical layers

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:44.708
will become more and more well-defined.

00:41:44.708 --> 00:41:48.960
So this is a snapshot
of all the cell types

00:41:48.960 --> 00:41:50.530
that we have if we just aged

00:41:50.530 --> 00:41:52.850
these brain organoids
for about four month.

00:41:52.850 --> 00:41:56.320
We have mostly glutamergic,
these excitatory neurons

00:41:56.320 --> 00:41:59.230
and you start to see two
populations in there,

00:41:59.230 --> 00:42:02.900
so these would be upper
and lower cortical layers,

00:42:02.900 --> 00:42:05.898
but we also have
inhibitory neurons as well.

00:42:05.898 --> 00:42:09.770
It's more a population
of GABAergic neurons.

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:12.010
There are progenitor cells
that continue to produce,

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:13.620
and at that stage, we start to see

00:42:13.620 --> 00:42:15.440
some glia cells, or astrocytes.

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:19.080
These are the cell types
that helps on the formation

00:42:19.080 --> 00:42:22.385
of these complex networks
that I'm gonna show you

00:42:22.385 --> 00:42:25.190
how they behave later on.

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:29.740
So this is all good, but I
need live cells to recreate

00:42:29.740 --> 00:42:33.217
those brain organoids in a
dish, and the problem is,

00:42:33.217 --> 00:42:36.740
there is no live cells
from the Neanderthals.

00:42:36.740 --> 00:42:38.520
So that poses a big problem:

00:42:38.520 --> 00:42:41.280
how can we recreate a Neanderthal mind

00:42:41.280 --> 00:42:43.655
if we don't have the
raw material for that?

00:42:43.655 --> 00:42:47.241
So, we turn to genetics
since we have their genome.

00:42:47.241 --> 00:42:49.880
One thing that is possible to do,

00:42:49.880 --> 00:42:52.178
is compare the genome of the Neanderthals

00:42:52.178 --> 00:42:55.744
to modern humans, and we
have thousands of them,

00:42:55.744 --> 00:42:59.510
and ask, what are the differences
between those genomes?

00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:02.446
What is it specific to modern humans

00:43:02.446 --> 00:43:07.446
that were positive selected
in us, compared to them?

00:43:08.190 --> 00:43:10.785
So, if we look across all the genes,

00:43:10.785 --> 00:43:14.290
we end up with about 200 genes,

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:18.216
and this is, many people have
been mining this data set

00:43:18.216 --> 00:43:21.460
and these are the genes that are different

00:43:21.460 --> 00:43:24.087
between modern humans and Neanderthals.

00:43:24.087 --> 00:43:26.900
Instead of looking for all these genes,

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:30.810
we decided to narrow down
this list to three genes,

00:43:30.810 --> 00:43:32.050
because we asked, what are the ones

00:43:32.050 --> 00:43:34.610
that are highly expressed
during the early stages

00:43:34.610 --> 00:43:36.782
of neural development
and what are the ones

00:43:36.782 --> 00:43:40.830
that we know if they are
mutated in modern humans,

00:43:40.830 --> 00:43:43.230
will lead to a neurological disorder?

00:43:43.230 --> 00:43:45.810
And these are the three
genes, these two here

00:43:45.810 --> 00:43:48.356
are synaptic genes, to
help how the synaptic

00:43:48.356 --> 00:43:50.880
or the connections between
neurons are formed,

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:52.707
and that one is a very interesting one

00:43:52.707 --> 00:43:54.490
'cause they start very early

00:43:54.490 --> 00:43:59.490
and it's a master regulator
of several downstream genes,

00:44:00.200 --> 00:44:05.150
it's a splicing regulator,
splicing protein.

00:44:05.150 --> 00:44:08.060
So, the way we do that
is using genome editing

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:10.210
and we use CRISPRs where we can go back

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:12.550
to one of our modern human cell lines

00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:17.280
and we can change or swap
the genetic information

00:44:17.280 --> 00:44:19.230
from the modern humans to the Neanderthal,

00:44:19.230 --> 00:44:22.156
so we Neanderthalize the cell lines,

00:44:22.156 --> 00:44:25.850
targeting those specific genes,
and at the end of the day

00:44:25.850 --> 00:44:27.370
we have Neanderthal brain organoids

00:44:27.370 --> 00:44:32.370
or Neanderthoids how we call
them, and we can compare.

00:44:32.445 --> 00:44:36.700
So, I mean we done that, we recreate that,

00:44:36.700 --> 00:44:39.233
and I'll show you some of the differences

00:44:39.233 --> 00:44:43.220
that we observe by comparing
them with the modern humans.

00:44:43.220 --> 00:44:46.080
So the first big difference is
at the gene expression level.

00:44:46.080 --> 00:44:48.560
What are the genes that
are up or downregulated,

00:44:48.560 --> 00:44:51.420
compared to us, and we
have a couple of them.

00:44:51.420 --> 00:44:53.761
The interesting part is
that they are all connected

00:44:53.761 --> 00:44:55.947
to brain development and several pathways

00:44:55.947 --> 00:44:58.081
that leads to brain formation.

00:44:58.081 --> 00:44:59.970
Now I'll point to some of them here,

00:44:59.970 --> 00:45:02.027
this is just a list of interesting genes

00:45:02.027 --> 00:45:04.880
that we are trying to understand.

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:08.100
There are genes such as nestin
which is a progenitor cell,

00:45:08.100 --> 00:45:10.730
early stages of neuro brain formations.

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:13.693
There are genes such as TBR1.

00:45:13.693 --> 00:45:16.440
This is a gene that has
been implicated in autism,

00:45:16.440 --> 00:45:20.331
for example, and they are
downregulated in Neanderthals.

00:45:20.331 --> 00:45:23.240
There are genes like OTX,
that when upregulated,

00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:26.340
might prone you to have
seizures or epilepsy,

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:29.380
so this all happens without
genetic modification,

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:31.930
I mean, it's just by
changing those early genes

00:45:31.930 --> 00:45:35.150
that you affect downstream
genetic signature

00:45:35.150 --> 00:45:38.828
that might lead to problems
such as autism or epilepsy.

00:45:38.828 --> 00:45:41.840
So, I told you about one of the genes

00:45:41.840 --> 00:45:43.247
that are actually a master regulator

00:45:43.247 --> 00:45:48.247
and controls how gene expression
or splicing is regulated,

00:45:49.290 --> 00:45:51.200
and this is a gene called NOVA1,

00:45:51.200 --> 00:45:56.200
and this is a reconstruction
of the protein

00:45:56.220 --> 00:45:59.623
attached to the RNA, and
exactly the base pair

00:45:59.623 --> 00:46:04.410
from the DNA that changes
out of that conformation

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:07.970
and as a consequence, the RNA splicing

00:46:07.970 --> 00:46:09.810
would be affected as well.

00:46:09.810 --> 00:46:12.920
And we are looking into
these outer splicing factors

00:46:12.920 --> 00:46:16.400
and we realized that there is
a lot of information in there.

00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:19.879
Some genes, like HOMER1, this
is another synaptic gene,

00:46:19.879 --> 00:46:22.820
have a different isoforms between humans

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:25.146
and Neanderthals during development.

00:46:25.146 --> 00:46:30.146
Other genes, and these
are actual target of NOVA1

00:46:30.850 --> 00:46:35.120
such as GNAS or BIN1, so
these are genes involving

00:46:35.120 --> 00:46:37.537
epigenetic regulation for example.

00:46:37.537 --> 00:46:39.630
They create a new isoform

00:46:39.630 --> 00:46:41.660
that's only present in Neanderthals.

00:46:41.660 --> 00:46:45.408
Modern humans lost that isoform
from that specific protein.

00:46:45.408 --> 00:46:47.900
So these are quite
interesting observations

00:46:47.900 --> 00:46:50.530
at the gene expression level.

00:46:50.530 --> 00:46:53.711
What happens to these brain
organoids if they have that?

00:46:53.711 --> 00:46:56.430
So the morphology's quite interesting.

00:46:56.430 --> 00:46:59.245
They start quite similar but
as they progress in time,

00:46:59.245 --> 00:47:01.877
you can tell that the
morphology changes a lot,

00:47:01.877 --> 00:47:05.700
so why are the modern
human's brain organoids

00:47:05.700 --> 00:47:09.224
become sphere, increase in
size and start to mature,

00:47:09.224 --> 00:47:12.687
Neanderthal brain organoids
have this kind of popcorn shape

00:47:12.687 --> 00:47:16.678
and you can measure the diameter of them,

00:47:16.678 --> 00:47:19.300
how they grow, and already we can see

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:21.410
that the Neanderthal organoids

00:47:21.410 --> 00:47:23.210
probably have some kind of cell death

00:47:23.210 --> 00:47:27.978
or some problems to develop,
compared to modern humans.

00:47:27.978 --> 00:47:31.630
Also, the size of these
spheres is different

00:47:31.630 --> 00:47:34.040
but also I mean the way those spheres

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:39.320
are shaped, which might point
it out to some differences

00:47:39.320 --> 00:47:43.430
as I said, in cell death or apoptosis,

00:47:43.430 --> 00:47:46.760
but also in migration,
the way the cells migrate.

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:48.520
So just by looking at these pictures,

00:47:48.520 --> 00:47:50.162
we can tell that there
is migration defects

00:47:50.162 --> 00:47:51.717
and there is a way to test that.

00:47:51.717 --> 00:47:53.513
You can plate some of these cells,

00:47:53.513 --> 00:47:56.220
and let them migrate by themselves,

00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:58.847
and what we observe is
that the Neanderthal cells,

00:47:58.847 --> 00:48:02.210
they have a defecting migration.

00:48:02.210 --> 00:48:07.210
They migrate slower but they
go farther than human cells.

00:48:07.610 --> 00:48:10.940
So even a small migration might affect

00:48:10.940 --> 00:48:15.490
your entire brain's
trajectory during development.

00:48:15.490 --> 00:48:17.060
So if you look at the neurons,

00:48:17.060 --> 00:48:19.522
I mean we also see a
difference in specific subtype

00:48:19.522 --> 00:48:22.403
of populations from the cortex of,

00:48:22.403 --> 00:48:24.780
this is one of the cortical layers,

00:48:24.780 --> 00:48:28.680
and we observed that SATB2,
a neuron that participates

00:48:28.680 --> 00:48:30.560
on intracortical communication

00:48:30.560 --> 00:48:33.870
as well as intracommunications
between layers,

00:48:33.870 --> 00:48:35.659
it is dramatically reduced

00:48:35.659 --> 00:48:40.430
in the Neanderthal cell
lines compared to controls.

00:48:40.430 --> 00:48:43.031
So, everything is all about morphology

00:48:43.031 --> 00:48:46.670
and how the cells behave or
the shape of these organoids.

00:48:46.670 --> 00:48:49.420
What about the function,
can we actually measure

00:48:49.420 --> 00:48:53.400
how the communication of the
network has been affected?

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:55.130
So to do that, we use a tool

00:48:55.130 --> 00:48:56.950
that is called a multielectrode array,

00:48:56.950 --> 00:48:59.240
where we plate these brain
organoids into multielectrodes

00:48:59.240 --> 00:49:02.936
into the bottom of those
dishes and we can record,

00:49:02.936 --> 00:49:07.438
we gain an activity map
as well as a raster plot

00:49:07.438 --> 00:49:10.713
and every trace here,
it's when a neuron spikes,

00:49:10.713 --> 00:49:15.220
and if you have several
spikes at the same time,

00:49:15.220 --> 00:49:17.522
we call that a burst,
and when bursts spikes

00:49:17.522 --> 00:49:21.080
in the same channel we
call it a synchrony event.

00:49:21.080 --> 00:49:23.430
And since we can keep them alive,

00:49:23.430 --> 00:49:26.031
we can see that they
evolve, and we did that,

00:49:26.031 --> 00:49:30.150
and when we start, we actually
didn't have one to compare,

00:49:30.150 --> 00:49:32.670
so I'm showing here just some of the work

00:49:32.670 --> 00:49:34.380
that we did in 2D, this is,

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:36.261
we dialed a three dimension restructure,

00:49:36.261 --> 00:49:41.261
and most of the data,
it is below five hertz,

00:49:41.660 --> 00:49:45.390
so this is just a average
measure of the brain activity,

00:49:45.390 --> 00:49:48.430
so what is the idea, what is our goal?

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:52.540
So a mouse brain is about
18 hertz, and a monkey brain

00:49:52.540 --> 00:49:55.250
is about 20 hertz, so other people

00:49:55.250 --> 00:49:57.319
have also created different
protocols for brain organoids

00:49:57.319 --> 00:50:02.319
and although they can also keep
them alive for a long period

00:50:02.680 --> 00:50:07.100
of time, they were not able to
see an increase in activity,

00:50:07.100 --> 00:50:09.836
suggesting that there is some
problems with maturation.

00:50:09.836 --> 00:50:13.910
But, we are glad that
the protocol we have,

00:50:13.910 --> 00:50:15.814
we were able not only to keep them alive

00:50:15.814 --> 00:50:19.285
but to reach a level of
activity that's much higher

00:50:19.285 --> 00:50:23.342
than was ever recorded before in vitro,

00:50:23.342 --> 00:50:26.828
so if you have that much level of activity

00:50:26.828 --> 00:50:30.740
in synaptogenesis going on,
it means that you can record

00:50:30.740 --> 00:50:33.540
something else, and this is what we call

00:50:33.540 --> 00:50:35.420
brain oscillations or brainwaves,

00:50:35.420 --> 00:50:37.810
the activity that can actually measure

00:50:37.810 --> 00:50:42.347
through the skulls using
electroencephalogram or EEG.

00:50:42.347 --> 00:50:46.380
So we can actually measure those EEG waves

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:49.589
from these brain organoids,
and we can compare them

00:50:49.589 --> 00:50:54.589
to preterm babies, so we
created these machine learning

00:50:54.660 --> 00:50:58.243
algorithm and we train that
in an unsupervised way,

00:50:58.243 --> 00:51:03.024
by exposing them to different
EEGs from preterm babies,

00:51:03.024 --> 00:51:07.241
and asking the machine to
tell the age of the person.

00:51:07.241 --> 00:51:09.962
So once the machine has
done that, we feed them

00:51:09.962 --> 00:51:13.420
with our brain organoids' EEG and we ask,

00:51:13.420 --> 00:51:16.278
what are the predicted
age of the organoids?

00:51:16.278 --> 00:51:20.640
So, this is how the machine will do

00:51:20.640 --> 00:51:23.440
in a perfect condition, in the red trace.

00:51:23.440 --> 00:51:27.640
The data is actually on
the black trace as well.

00:51:27.640 --> 00:51:30.210
You can see that we have
a very good prediction,

00:51:30.210 --> 00:51:35.000
above 25 weeks, and the reason why

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.530
the machine is not good
to predict below that,

00:51:37.530 --> 00:51:40.420
is because we simply don't have any data

00:51:40.420 --> 00:51:43.890
from human preterm babies below that.

00:51:43.890 --> 00:51:47.078
The babies will die, and we
don't have a way to record

00:51:47.078 --> 00:51:49.518
in utero, that is non-invasive.

00:51:49.518 --> 00:51:51.730
So that's why we don't
have a good prediction.

00:51:51.730 --> 00:51:54.350
But what is the prediction
that we can have?

00:51:54.350 --> 00:51:57.542
And I'll show you just one
example of one of the parameters

00:51:57.542 --> 00:52:00.889
from the EEG which is the
space between the interval

00:52:00.889 --> 00:52:04.115
of activities, so if we just look

00:52:04.115 --> 00:52:08.373
at an adult EEG here,
so it's quite complex.

00:52:08.373 --> 00:52:10.650
This is a preterm baby, you see

00:52:10.650 --> 00:52:12.791
these spontaneous activity transient

00:52:12.791 --> 00:52:15.680
followed by a quiescent period

00:52:15.680 --> 00:52:18.196
where the brain is just silent,
when you're super young,

00:52:18.196 --> 00:52:21.886
and here is our brain
organoid, so the brain organoid

00:52:21.886 --> 00:52:25.770
is much similar to a preterm
baby than to adult brain,

00:52:25.770 --> 00:52:27.360
so that's what we're modeling.

00:52:27.360 --> 00:52:29.868
We're modeling early
stages of neurodevelopment.

00:52:29.868 --> 00:52:34.868
So, as we grow older, the
interval between those activities

00:52:34.949 --> 00:52:37.833
become shorter and
shorter, that's why we have

00:52:37.833 --> 00:52:40.545
this complex EEG in adult.

00:52:40.545 --> 00:52:42.900
So the organoid, as we age the organoid,

00:52:42.900 --> 00:52:46.919
the interval also reduces,
and reduces to a level

00:52:46.919 --> 00:52:50.852
that gets close to that
red bar, about 40 weeks

00:52:50.852 --> 00:52:55.534
or nine month, that's
equivalent to a newborn

00:52:55.534 --> 00:52:59.910
healthy human baby, so
that's what we can get

00:52:59.910 --> 00:53:01.886
with these human organoids.

00:53:01.886 --> 00:53:04.965
So now that we have lots
of activity to compare,

00:53:04.965 --> 00:53:08.398
I mean, how does the
Neanderthal brain organoids

00:53:08.398 --> 00:53:10.071
compare to modern humans?

00:53:10.071 --> 00:53:13.640
So we have been studying
that from different angles,

00:53:13.640 --> 00:53:17.110
and I'll first start by
showing what is the level

00:53:17.110 --> 00:53:20.364
of synaptogenesis, how
many brain cell connections

00:53:20.364 --> 00:53:23.847
the Neanderthals can make
compared to modern humans?

00:53:23.847 --> 00:53:26.920
And we see that it's almost 50% reduction

00:53:26.920 --> 00:53:30.562
which is similar to someone
with autism, for example.

00:53:30.562 --> 00:53:32.690
So definitely a lower level

00:53:32.690 --> 00:53:34.980
of synapsis compared to controls.

00:53:34.980 --> 00:53:37.530
We also measured them on
the multielectrode arrays,

00:53:37.530 --> 00:53:40.114
and what we have here in this part

00:53:40.114 --> 00:53:44.350
is just the raster plot, the activity map,

00:53:44.350 --> 00:53:46.861
and then some of the
contrafigurations that we have.

00:53:46.861 --> 00:53:48.760
The number of spikes,
the level of activity

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:52.619
per neuron per minute, is way reduced

00:53:52.619 --> 00:53:55.986
to what we expect for an isogenic control.

00:53:55.986 --> 00:53:59.970
The same is true for the
firing rate for these neurons

00:53:59.970 --> 00:54:02.265
is also reduced compared
to isogenic controls,

00:54:02.265 --> 00:54:05.347
which again points to the
fact that these networks

00:54:05.347 --> 00:54:08.877
are just not good enough,
or not mature enough,

00:54:08.877 --> 00:54:11.653
to the level that we would
expect from modern humans.

00:54:11.653 --> 00:54:15.615
So, I hope I could tell you that,

00:54:15.615 --> 00:54:19.010
by recreating these
Neanderthal brain in a dish

00:54:19.010 --> 00:54:22.668
we could say that they have
differences in morphology,

00:54:22.668 --> 00:54:25.569
synaptogenesis, even at the network level,

00:54:25.569 --> 00:54:28.500
but the question is, are those differences

00:54:28.500 --> 00:54:32.147
better or worse than the modern human's?

00:54:32.147 --> 00:54:35.260
And I made like some analogies with autism

00:54:35.260 --> 00:54:37.130
and other neurological
disorders, but the truth is

00:54:37.130 --> 00:54:40.514
that we don't know, so we
have been looking at that

00:54:40.514 --> 00:54:42.539
using different experimental models,

00:54:42.539 --> 00:54:46.284
and I'll just show you one
thing that we are excited about,

00:54:46.284 --> 00:54:49.150
and this came from this
idea that if you have

00:54:49.150 --> 00:54:51.068
brain oscillations from
people working together,

00:54:51.068 --> 00:54:53.864
they might actually synchronize
or they are more prone

00:54:53.864 --> 00:54:58.864
to work if your friend is
with you, than a stranger,

00:55:00.297 --> 00:55:02.580
which suggests that to achieve something,

00:55:02.580 --> 00:55:07.340
to achieve a specific goal,
it's better to work with someone

00:55:07.340 --> 00:55:11.260
that you like, so we have been tagging

00:55:11.260 --> 00:55:14.290
these human brain organoids into robots,

00:55:14.290 --> 00:55:17.573
so that's a way for the robot
to experiment in the world,

00:55:17.573 --> 00:55:20.480
and we are doing that in two ways.

00:55:20.480 --> 00:55:22.420
The first step is just teaching

00:55:22.420 --> 00:55:24.370
the organoid how to move a robot,

00:55:24.370 --> 00:55:26.785
and that's what you're going
to be seeing in this video.

00:55:26.785 --> 00:55:31.540
So this is a robot that is
being moving all the legs,

00:55:31.540 --> 00:55:34.010
just by the frequency of oscillations

00:55:34.010 --> 00:55:35.663
coming from the human brain organoid,

00:55:35.663 --> 00:55:39.510
so the idea is now to do the second step,

00:55:39.510 --> 00:55:41.260
which is to create the feedback loop,

00:55:41.260 --> 00:55:43.324
so the organoid can
actually learn something

00:55:43.324 --> 00:55:47.580
and the robot can tell by
experiencing the world.

00:55:47.580 --> 00:55:50.100
So soon we're going to be
doing the same experiments

00:55:50.100 --> 00:55:52.115
using Neanderthal brain organoids.

00:55:52.115 --> 00:55:54.970
We can see if the robot can actually

00:55:54.970 --> 00:55:58.176
learn something better
or not, than humans.

00:55:58.176 --> 00:56:03.176
So, I'll finish here by
summarizing that we have a model,

00:56:03.296 --> 00:56:05.930
brain organoid model
coming from stem cells

00:56:05.930 --> 00:56:07.908
that can recapitulate human development.

00:56:07.908 --> 00:56:12.411
We can reconstruct evolutionary
steps that recapitulate

00:56:12.411 --> 00:56:17.411
key features of the Neanderthal
development, we think so,

00:56:19.280 --> 00:56:23.090
and this might be a paradigm for learning

00:56:23.090 --> 00:56:25.998
if you put them back to
a robot or something.

00:56:25.998 --> 00:56:29.270
So these are Cleber and Priscilla,

00:56:29.270 --> 00:56:31.099
these are the brain masters in the lab,

00:56:31.099 --> 00:56:33.579
they are the ones who
developed these nice protocols

00:56:33.579 --> 00:56:36.330
that everybody's excited about,

00:56:36.330 --> 00:56:39.221
and these are my collaborators
for this project.

00:56:39.221 --> 00:56:42.033
Both Katerina Semendeferi,
Yeo Lab, the VOYTEKlab,

00:56:42.033 --> 00:56:45.430
and Eric Green who helped us

00:56:45.430 --> 00:56:48.247
on the general genomic
analysis of Neanderthals.

00:56:48.247 --> 00:56:50.400
And these are my funding agencies,

00:56:50.400 --> 00:56:52.387
and I'll stop here, thank you very much.

00:56:52.387 --> 00:56:55.470
(audience applauds)

